! While sitting, keep your back and shoulders

Festivals are a time of celebr ation. They bring joy and happiness. We shar e 
this joy and happiness with our family and friends.
India is called the 'land of festivals'. Man y festivals are celebr ated in our

National Festivals
Our national festivals are the festivals celebr ated all over the nation i.e. India. 
These festivals give us pride and joy of being Indian. The national festivals we 
celebr ate are– Republic Day, Independence Day and Gandhi Jayanti.

Republic Day–th
 Republic Day is celebr ated on 26 of 
Januar y every year. Our constitution came into th

New Delhi.
Independence Day– We celebrate our th
Independence Day on 15  of Augus t every 
year. India got free from British rule on this th

Gandhi Jayanti – Gandhi Jayanti is celebr ated on nd

Religious Festivals
Religious festivals are connect ed with religions. In India, all the religions are equally 
respect ed. People of all religions celebr ate their festivals with great joy. Holi, 
Diwali, Dussehr a, Eid, Gurpur ab, Chris tmas etc. are some of the religious festivals 
celebr ated all over the country.
Holi–  Holi is known as the festival of colour s. It is 
celebr ated in the memor y of Bhak t Prahlad. This 
festival also mark s the end of winter. People apply 
colour s and throw colour ed water on each other . 
Gujhiy a is a special sweet eaten on Holi.

Diwali– Diwali is a festival of lights. It is a major festival 
of Hindus. It marks the return of Lord Rama to 
Ayodhya after 14 years of exile. People decorate their 
houses, shops and offices with colourful lights, 
flowers and earthen lamp s (diyas). Sweets and gifts 
are exchang ed on this festival. Lord Ganesha and 
Goddess Lakshmi are worshipped at nigh t.
Dussehr a– Dussehr a is celebr ated to mark the victory of Lord Rama over Ravana. It 
is ten days long festival. Ramlila is staged for first nine days. On the tenth day 
effigies of Ravana, Kumbhak arna and Meghnad 
are burn t.
Dussehr a is celebr ated as Durga Puja also. On 
the tenth day idols of Goddess Durga are

is celebr ated after one mon th of fasting. This 
mon th of fasting is known as Ramz an.
On Eid, people wear new clothes and go to 
mosque to pray. They hug each other and wish 
'Eid Mubarak'. Special sweet dish called

They are celebr ated to mark the birthda ys of the

Gurpur ab is the birthda y of Guru Nank Dev Ji. He 
was the first guru of Sikhs.
On this day, the Sikhs assemble in Gurudw aras 
Chris tmas–  Chris tmas is celebr ated to mark the birth of th
lord Jesus Chris t. It is celebr ated on 25 of December 
every year. People go to Church and offer special 
prayers. Carols are sung and candles are lit everywher e. 
It is belie ved that Santa Claus brings gifts for childr en on

Harvest Festivals
Harvest festival are celebr ated when farmer s gather their crops from the fields. 
Some import ant harvest festivals are : 
Pongal– It is the harvest festival of Tamil Nadu. Rain God, Sun 
God and Cow are worshipped on this festival.
Onam–  It is the harvest festival of Kerala. People mak e beautiful 
'Rang oli' on this festival. Races of snak e boats are the main 
attraction of Onam.
Baisakhi–  Baisakhi is celebr ated on 13th or 14th of April every 
year. This festival mark s the time for harvest of Rabi crops in 
Punjab and nearby states. People celebrate this day by 
performing Bhangr a and Gidda dances.
